<p>eople have asked me for advice on writing nonfiction online, so here are some tips:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Divide things into small chunks
Nobody likes walls of text. By this point most people know that you should have short, sweet paragraphs with line breaks between them. The shorter, the better. If youâ€™re ever debating whether or not to end the paragraph and add a line break, err on the side of â€œyesâ€.
Once you understand this principle, you can generalize it to other aspects of your writing. For example, I stole the Last Psychiatristâ€™s style of section breaks â€“ bold headers sayingÂ I.,Â II.,Â III., etc. Now instead of just paragraph breaks, you have two forms of break â€“ paragraph break and section break. On some of my longest posts, including theÂ Anti-Reactionary FAQÂ andÂ Meditations on Moloch, I add athirdÂ level of break â€“ in the first case, a supersection level in large fonts, in the latter, a subsection level with an underlinedÂ First,Â Second,Â etc. Again, if youâ€™re ever debating more versus fewer breaks, err on the side of â€œmoreâ€.
Finishing a paragraph or section gives people a micro-burst of accomplishment and reward. It helps them chunk the basic insight together and remember it for later. You want people to be going â€“ â€œokay, insight, good, another insight, good, another insight, goodâ€ and then eventually you can tie all of the insights together into a high-level insight. Then you can start over, until eventually at the end you tie all of the high-level insights together. Itâ€™s nice and structured and easy to work with. If theyâ€™re just following a winding stream of thought wherever itâ€™s going, itâ€™ll take a lot more mental work and theyâ€™ll get bored and wander off.
Remember that clickbait comes from big media corporations optimizing for easy readability, and that the epitome of clickbait is the listicle. But the insight of the listicle applies even to much more sophisticated intellectual pieces â€“ people are much happier to read a long thing if they can be tricked into thinking itâ€™s a series of small things.</li>
  <li>Variety is the spice of life
This is really closely linked to the last tip. Your brain gets bored if it has to focus on the same thing for too long. But you can get around that by making an activity look like many different things. Sometimes this is as simple and as dumb as putting Roman numeral one, Roman numeral two, etc at natural breaks in the article, and then your brain thinks â€œOh, I guess there are two different things hereâ€. But other times you actually have to vary the reading experience.
Again, the clickbaiters are our gurus â€“ they intersperse images throughout their content. The images arenâ€™t always very useful, they donâ€™t always add much, but now itâ€™s not just a wall of text. Itâ€™s a wall of textÂ andÂ images.</li>
</ol>

<p>Watch the blue twirly thing until you forget how bored you are by this essay, then continue.
Or you can be more subtle. Break your flow. IncludeÂ links, so that the never-ending stream of black text on white background is broken up with some pretty blue. If you areÂ veryÂ desperate, italicize certain words to simulate the stresses of normal speech and turn the visual experience into a visual-auditory experience. Vary the form of your sentences, as perÂ Gary Provost:
    This sentence has five words. Here are five more words. Five-word sentences are fine. But several together become monotonous. Listen to what is happening. The writing is getting boring. The sound of it drones. Itâ€™s like a stuck record. The ear demands some variety. Now listen. I vary the sentence length, and I create music. Music. The writing sings. It has a pleasant rhythm, a lilt, a harmony. I use short sentences. And I use sentences of medium length. And sometimes, when I am certain the reader is rested, I will engage him with a sentence of considerable length, a sentence that burns with energy and builds with all the impetus of a crescendo, the roll of the drums, the crash of the cymbalsâ€“sounds that say listen to this, it is important. 
(Blockquotes are also a nice way to vary the reading experience)
But donâ€™t just vary the appearance of your writing. Vary the tone. If youâ€™re comfortable, shift between registers. When I wasÂ talking about SSRIs, I mentioned study after study after study â€“ and then, around the middle, I told a kind of funny story about the time I had a job interview with the author of one of the studies. It was a complete break with the tone of the piece, which is dangerous â€“ but my hope was that after having your mind dulled by twenty different pharmacology studies in a row, a quick first-person aside and silly story would be invigorating and give you the energy to wade through another twenty such studies.</p>
<ol>
  <li>Keep your flow of ideas strong
I lampshade my flow of ideas with a lot of words like â€œAlsoâ€, â€œButâ€, â€œNeverthelessâ€, â€œRelatedlyâ€, and â€œSoâ€ (when Iâ€™m feeling pretentious, also â€œThusâ€). These are the words your eighth-grade English teacher told you never to start paragraphs with. Your eighth-grade English teacher was wrong. If youâ€™re writing three paragraphs that are three different pieces of evidence for the same conclusion that youâ€™re going to present afterwards, make damn sure your readers know this. It could be as simple as:
Itâ€™s pretty obvious that X is true,Â andÂ we have lots of converging lines of evidence for this.Â Some of the best evidenceÂ comes from the field of augury.Â For example: 
First, A
Second, B
Third, C
Now, some people say that not-A,Â butÂ thatâ€™s totally wrong. It only looks like not-A,Â becauseÂ P.Â Likewise,Â althoughÂ Q might make it look like not-B, Q canâ€™t be trusted for several other reasons,Â for exampleÂ R.Â AndÂ not-C is too silly to even think about.Â SoÂ despiteÂ the objections you always hear, the augurical evidence for X is strong.
Even moreÂ evidence comes from the field of haruspicy.Â AllÂ four major haruspical schools hold X as a major principle. School 1 says X because of D. School 2 says X because of E. School 3 says X because of F.Â Andschool 4 says X because of G.Â So althoughÂ augury and haruspicy disagree on a lot, on the subject of X they are in complete accord.
Notice the underlined words holding up the structure of the argument. Not only is the argument nice and tight, but the role of each part in the whole is telegraphed beforehand. For example, the â€œnowâ€ that comes just after C is saying something like â€œTake a step back, Iâ€™m about to tell you something that might otherwise be controversial, but listen to what I have to sayâ€. And the â€œlikewiseâ€ just after P means something like â€œWe just got down talking about not-A because P, hereâ€™s another argument with about the same structureâ€. Before any of the facts are inserted, you already know where they fit into the structure. And youâ€™re able to abstract from the micro-level and get the bigger picture of some fact which is supported by both augury and haruspicy, which was the main point of the argument.
I overuse the world â€œactuallyâ€ really badly. Iâ€™m trying to cut down on it, but I donâ€™t want to stop completely. â€œActuallyâ€ is a great structural word. It distinguishes â€œHereâ€™s how things look, hereâ€™s whatâ€™s actually trueâ€. That sentence makes sense even without the â€œactuallyâ€, but I feel like the â€œactuallyâ€ holds my readersâ€™ hands through the process and makes the dichotomy better-defined.
Defend your flow of ideas at all costs. This might sound paradoxical after section 2, which was about how breaking flows is great. ItÂ isÂ kind of paradoxical, and itÂ issort of hard to explain, but itâ€™s the difference between â€œexcitingâ€ and â€œhorribleâ€. Eating a foreign cuisine can be exciting because itâ€™s so different from your usual fare; eating hot lava is evenÂ moreÂ different than your usual fare, but no longer fun. Play around with flow and variety, but never break the flow in aÂ jarringÂ way. And if you have to break a flow, make it the flow of your sentence, or the flow of your paragraph, butÂ not the flow of ideas.
I agonize a lot about where it is versus isnâ€™t appropriate to break the flow of ideas. Sometimes I use the really ugly solution of having an entire paragraph within parentheses, as if to say â€œI really wanted to bring this up here, but remember itâ€™s not actually part of the structure of this argument!â€
(this is a good meta-level example. I used the word â€œactuallyâ€ there, and I wanted to point it out as an example of what I was talking about before, but doing that would break the flow of this whole argument about how you shouldnâ€™t break the flow of things. So, in accordance with the prophecy, into a paragraph-long set of parentheses it goes. Iâ€™m starting to think maybe Iâ€™m not the best person to be giving writing adviceâ€¦)
But sometimes youâ€™ve just got to leave out an observation which would be interesting and helpful but not at that particular part of your argument. I think the phrase isÂ â€œkill your darlingsâ€.</li>
  <li>Learn what should and shouldnâ€™t be repeated.
A lot of the medical notes I read look like this:
 Mr. Smith presents to the ER for evaluation. He is a 24 year old man. He is complaining of chest pain. He was in the shower today when he slipped and fell. He was able to get up and make dinner. He says the chest pain started two hours later. He says has never had chest pain before. He took two aspirin. He says that did not help. He says the pain is 8/10 at this time. He says it is pretty bad, but that the pain of hearing these repetitive sentence structures is even worse. 
If two sentences in a row start with the same word, it sounds unwieldy. If three or four do, it sounds bizarre. If itâ€™s a whole paragraphâ€™s worth, people start questioning their own sanity and trying to claw their eyes out.
A counterexample: what about the paragraph just above, starting with â€œIf two sentencesâ€¦â€? I started with â€œifâ€ three times in a row, and it didnâ€™t sound bad at all! Whatâ€™s up?
Deliberate use of parallelismÂ is okay and even commendable. Usually this involves using the same structure to call attention to certain differences. You can tell if something is good parallelism by saying it aloud. When I say the paragraph above aloud, Iâ€™m using special intonation, especially in the places where the sentences differ (ie â€œtwoâ€, â€œthree or fourâ€, â€œwhole paragraphâ€™s worthâ€). Here your reader knows what youâ€™re trying to do and itâ€™s interesting. In the medical history example, thereâ€™s no deliberate attempt at parallelism in order to compare and contrast. Youâ€™re just doing the same thing again and again.
But itâ€™s not just about first words of sentences. Consider something like this:
 China has the largest population of any country in the world. It also has the largest military. Because of Chinaâ€™s powerful military, some of its neighbors are afraid of it. China has reassured its neighbors many times that itâ€™s peaceful, but theyâ€™re not convinced. 
This sounds off to me. The repetition of â€œlargest populationâ€ and â€œlargest militaryâ€ is done clumsily. There are a lot of ways to make it a virtuous parallelism â€“ for example â€œChina has the largest population â€“ and largest military â€“ in the worldâ€ or â€œChina has the largest population in the world; it also boasts the largest militaryâ€ â€“ but as it is, it just sounds weird. When you come to â€œlargest militaryâ€, thereâ€™s an immediate mental callback to â€œlargest populationâ€, but youâ€™re not sure why and itâ€™s just distracting.
Likewise, the repetition of â€œneighborsâ€ is weird. It could be solved by changing the second use to â€œthose neighborsâ€, which sort of telegraphs that you know youâ€™re repeating â€œneighborsâ€ and did it on purpose. Otherwise it has the same unfortunate dull-sounding cadence as the medical history.
You could also solve both those problems by just varying the structure enough that the problem goes away. For example:
 China is the most populous nation in the world. It also boasts the worldâ€™s largest military, which has provoked concern among other nations in the region. Although China has tried to reassure its neighbors of its peaceful intentions, they remain unconvinced. 
This is hard and really deserves a book-length treatment. Without the book, all I can say is to realize that any repetition of words and structures will stand out to your reader, and make sure that their standing-out emphasizes your point instead of just being confusing.</li>
  <li>Use microhumor
Youâ€™ve heard of microaggressions. Now try microhumor. Itâ€™s things that arenâ€™t ajokeÂ in the laugh-out-loud told-by-a-comedian sense, but still put the tiniest ghost of a smile on your readerâ€™s face while theyâ€™re skimming through them.
I learned this art from Dave Barry and Scott Adams, both of whom are humor writers and use normal macrohumor, but both of whom pepper the spaces in between jokes with microhumor besides. Your best best is to read everything theyâ€™ve written, your second best bet is to listen to me fumblingly try to explain it.
Hereâ€™s a paragraph from my â€œaboutâ€ page:
 Topics here tend to center vaguely around this meta-philosophical idea of how people evaluate arguments for their beliefs, and especially whether this process is spectacularly broken in a way that may or may not doom us all. 
There are a couple of things here that might qualify as microhumor. Take â€œespecially whether this process is spectacularly broken in a way that may or may not doom us allâ€. Itâ€™s not really aÂ joke. If I were a comedian and recited that sentence, you wouldnâ€™t start laughing. But itâ€™s kind of funny to be starting with what sounds like a pretty dry academic idea (â€œhow people evaluate arguments for their beliefsâ€ and whether the process is broken), and then confound expectations with an exaggerated (well, maybe) warning about it dooming us all. The phrase â€œmay or may not doom us allâ€ does the same thing on a smaller scale: â€œmay or may notâ€ is a pretty reserved, careful sounding phrase, whereas â€œdoom us allâ€ is obviously the opposite of reserved (I also like the similar construction â€œit might have sort of kind of been the worst idea everâ€).
You can actually go a long way toward microhumor just with hedge words (â€œvaguelyâ€, â€œsort ofâ€), exaggerations (â€œthe worst thing everâ€, â€œdoom us allâ€), and sometimes the combination of the two.
I think this microhumor stuff is really important, maybe the number one thing that separates really enjoyable writers from people who are technically proficient but still a chore to read. Think about it with a really simplistic behaviorist model where you keep doing things that give you little bursts of reward, and stop doing things that donâ€™t. There are only a couple of sources of reward in reading. One of them is getting important insights. Another is hearing things that support your ingroups or bash your outgroups. And a third â€“ maybe the biggest â€“ is humor. Who ever had trouble slogging through a really hilarious book of jokes?
Nobody can be super funny all the time, and an article on the economic crisis filled with man-walks-into-a-bar-style jokes would be jarring and weird. But micro-humor really works. It works at a background level where people donâ€™t notice it working, and it makes people keep coming back for more.
Humor is also disarming. Itâ€™s hard to hate somebody whoâ€™s making you laugh. I donâ€™t mean somebody whoâ€™s making bigoted jokes that offend you, or writing political cartoons about how awful your ingroup is. Those people are easy to hate. I mean somebody whoâ€™s makingÂ youÂ laugh, right now. If you can make people laugh while challenging their cherished beliefs, youâ€™ve got a tiny bit more good will than usual.</li>
  <li>Use concrete examples
Consider the following proposition:
In a study measuring whether implicit attitudes determine an outcome, you need to make sure the implicit attitudes arenâ€™t serving as accurate proxies for underlying fundamentals.
This is the thesis of one of my more popular posts,Â Perceptions Of Required Ability Act As A Proxy For Actual Required Ability, but I donâ€™tÂ presentÂ it like that. Instead, I start by saying:
 Imagine a study with the following methodology. You survey a bunch of people to get their perceptions of who is a smoker (â€œ97% of his close friends agree Bob smokesâ€). Then you correlate those numbers with who gets lung cancer. Your statistics program lights up like a Christmas tree with a bunch of super-strong correlations. You conclude â€œPerception of being a smoker causes lung cancerâ€, and make up a theory about how negative stereotypes of smokers cause stress which depresses the immune system. The media reports that as â€œSmoking Doesnâ€™t Cause Cancer, Stereotypes Doâ€. 
Whether or not you understood or agreed with the abstract version thesis, you (hopefully) find the problems with the nicotine example intuitively obvious. Now if I give you the principle â€œin a study measuring whether implicit attitudes determine an outcome, you need to make sure the implicit attitudes arenâ€™t serving as accurate proxies for underlying fundamentalsâ€, that principle makes sense and you will tend to agree with it. Now we can move on to harder problems, like the actual study in the post, where itâ€™sÂ notÂ as obvious and where a lot of people thought theyâ€™d proven that the implicit attitude determined the outcome.
If youâ€™re going to be making a complicated point, start with a concrete example. If youâ€™re going to be making aÂ veryÂ complicated point, start with aÂ lotÂ of concrete examples. When I wroteÂ Meditations on Moloch, probably the most complicated point Iâ€™ve ever tried to express on this blog, I began with fourteen different examples before I even started trying to express the underlying principle. I hoped that readers would be able to triangulate my point by finding what all fourteen examples had in common, and most of them did.
This is related to an idea I keep stressing here, which is that people rarely have consistent meta-level principles. Instead, theyâ€™ll endorse the meta-level principle that supports their object-level beliefs at any given moment.Â The exampleÂ I keep giving is how when the federal government was anti-gay, conservatives talked about the pressing need for federal intervention and liberals insisted on statesâ€™ rights; when the federal government became pro-gay, liberals talked about the pressing need for federal intervention and conservatives insisted on statesâ€™ rights.
So if you want to convince someone of a meta-level principle, you need to build it up from examples that support it. And if you want the principle to be well-founded and stable under reflective equilibrium, you also need to present the examples thatÂ donâ€™tÂ support it and explain why you didnâ€™t make your principle out of those instead.
And if you want to convince somebody that their meta-level principle is wrong, the quickest and most effective way to do it is to show that itÂ proves too much, then provide them with a better principle that preserves the things they want but doesnâ€™t prove things they donâ€™t want.
But my point is that all of this has to be done on the object-level, with the excursions to the meta-level level being few, far-between, and justified with extensive application to the object-level. Otherwise youâ€™re too likely to shoot off into the entirely abstract and end up sounding like Hegel:
 The good is the idea, or unity of the conception of the will with the particular will. Abstract right, well-being, the subjectivity of consciousness, and the contingency of external reality, are in their independent and separate existences superseded in this unity, although in their real essence they are contained in it and preserved. This unity is realized freedom, the absolute final cause of the world. Every stage is properly the idea, but the earlier steps contain the idea only in more abstract form. The I, as person, is already the idea, although in its most abstract guise. The good is the idea more completely determined; it is the unity of the conception of will with the particular will. It is not something abstractly right, but has a real content, whose substance constitutes both right and well-being. 
Please donâ€™t end up sounding like Hegel.
And a free tip for this: use words like â€œmeâ€ and â€œyouâ€ instead of â€œa personâ€ or â€œsomeoneâ€. Compare:
â€œIf someone does the calculations with this methodology, the result will probably be nonsense.â€
Versus:
â€œIf you do the calculations with that methodology, youâ€™ll probably end up with nonsense.â€
I think the second sounds snappier and more concrete.</li>
  <li>Figure out who youâ€™re trying to convince, then use the right tribal signals
Your role model in this (and in nothing else) should be Donald Trump. Think about it. He supports Planned Parenthood, doesnâ€™t want to cut entitlement programs, condemns Dubya and the Iraq war, supports affirmative action, supports medical marijuana, etc. If somebody were to tell you last year that a man with those policy positions would not only be leading the Republican primary, but leading even among the most conservative voters, youâ€™d think they were crazy. The rest of the country has been trying to convince conservative Republicans to be more comfortable with those positions for decades, and weâ€™ve failed miserably. Now Trump just waltzes in and everyone is like â€œYeah, okay, sureâ€?
The secret of Trumpâ€™s success is that most conservative Republicans donâ€™t really care about medical marijuana (or whatever) for its own sake. They care because opposing medical marijuana symbolizes membership in their tribe, they feel like their tribe is persecuted, they have a fierce loyalty to their tribe, and darned if theyâ€™re going to support somebody who doesnâ€™t use the right shibboleths.
Trump throws them a bone. He says things like â€œillegal immigrants are rapistsâ€ that no moderate or liberal would ever say, things that would horrify them. He usesÂ all the affectations of being working class. He may not quite prove heâ€™s â€œone of usâ€, but he very effectively proves heâ€™s not Just A Typical Outgroup Member. When Trump says â€œLegalize medical marijuanaâ€, they donâ€™t hear â€œIâ€™m yet another RINO liberal pansy who hates Christian values and wants everybody to become reefer-smoking hippiesâ€. So they only hear something boring about the regulations around pain relief medication â€“ and who cares about those?
Trumpâ€™s Law is that if you want to convince people notorious for being unconvinceable, half the battle is using the right tribal signals to sound like youâ€™re one of them.
For example, when Iâ€™m trying to convince conservatives, I veer my signaling way to the right. I startedÂ my defense of trigger warningsÂ with â€œI complain a lot about the social justice movementâ€. Then I cited Jezebel and various Ethnic Studies professors being against trigger warnings. Then I tried to argue that trigger warnings actually go together well with strong versions of freedom of speech. At this point I havenâ€™t even started arguing in favor of trigger warnings, Iâ€™ve just set up an unexpected terrain in which trigger warnings can be seen as a conservative thing supported by people who like free speech and donâ€™t like social justice, and opposition to trigger warnings can be seen as the sort of very liberal thing that people like Jezebel and Ethnic Studies professors support. The important thing isnâ€™t that I convince anyone that trigger warnings are really on the right â€“ thatâ€™s a tall order â€“ but that the rightists reading my argument feel like Iâ€™m working with them rather than against them. Iâ€™m not just another leftist saying â€œSupport trigger warnings because itâ€™s the leftist thing and you should be leftist and everyone on the right is terrible!â€
My reward was seeing a bunch of hard-core anti-social-justice types trip over themselves in horror at actually being kind of convinced, which was pretty funny.
On the other hand, when Iâ€™m trying to convince feminists of something, IÂ start withÂ a trigger warning â€“ partly because I genuinely believe itâ€™s a good idea and those posts can be triggering, but also partly because starting with a trigger warning is a tribal signal that people on the right rarely use. It means that either Iâ€™m on their side, or Iâ€™m being unusually respectful to it. In this itâ€™s a lot like Trump saying illegal immigrants are rapists â€“ something the outgroup would never, ever do.
(And thatâ€™s not just my theory â€“ Iâ€™ve gotten lots of angry comments about the trigger warnings from people further right than me, saying that using them makes me an idiot or a pushover or a cuck or something. I am always happy to get these comments, because it means the signaling value of using trigger warnings remains intact.)
Crossing tribal signaling boundaries is by far the most important persuasive technique I know, besides which none of the others even deserve to be called persuasive techniques at all. But to make it work, you have to actually understand the signals, and you have to have at least an ounce of honest sympathy for the other side. You canâ€™t just be like â€œHELLO THERE, FELLOW LIBERALS! LETâ€™S CREATE INTRUSIVE BIG GOVERNMENT AGENCIES TOGETHER! BUT BEFORE WE DO, I HAVE SOMETHING I WANT TO TELL YOU ABOUT THE SECOND AMENDMENTâ€¦â€
Which I guess means that being able to consider both sides of an issueÂ sort ofgives you superpowers. Thatâ€™s pretty encouraging.</li>
  <li>Anticipate and defuse counterarguments
Hereâ€™s something Iâ€™ve noticed. Something like:
 Alice:Â We need to invade Syria. I know that thereâ€™s always the risk of creating a Iraq-style power vacuum in these situations, but the threat from ISIS is too great. 
Sounds a whole lot better than something like:
 Alice:Â We need to invade Syria. Bob:Â But isnâ€™t there a risk that will create a Iraq-style power vacuum? Alice:Â The threat from ISIS is too great. 
The second one sounds too much like Alice hadnâ€™t really thought about the power vacuum thing, Bob called her on it, and she kind of blew him off with a tangentially related point. The first one sounds more like Alice is a careful thinker who has weighed all the risks and benefits and finally decided in favor of invasion. This is true even though Aliceâ€™s reasoning is the same in both situations.
Or what about this:
Alice:Â We need to invade Syria. I know that thereâ€™s always the risk of creating a Iraq-style power vacuum in these situations, but the threat from ISIS is too great. Bob:Â I know the threat from ISIS is serious, but Iâ€™m still really worried about that power vacuum thing.
Bob sounds kind of weak here. Come on, Bob. AliceÂ alreadyÂ raised the power vacuum issue! Weâ€™reÂ done withÂ that!
The moral of the story is that you sound a lot more credible, and your opponents a lot less persuasive, if youâ€™re the one who brings the possible counterarguments up yourself. This is trueÂ regardlessÂ of how effective your countercounterarguments are.
Thereâ€™s also a visibility advantage. Suppose Alice puts her argument on her blog. Bob quotes her and puts his counterargument on his blog. Maybe the readers of Bobâ€™s blog wonâ€™t read Aliceâ€™s blog where they can see her countercounterargument. Maybe they donâ€™t even read the comments of Bobâ€™s blog. If Alice addressed the obvious counterarguments in her first post, Bob has been preempted from blogging about them separately, or at least has lost his low-hanging fruit and has to stretch further before he finds something he can talk about. And if he does quote Alice, all the countercounterarguments against his point will be right there for his readers.
This isnâ€™t just good rhetorical practice, itâ€™s good epistemic practice. A lot of Internet arguments are the same ten or twenty issues re-examined time after time after time after time. If youâ€™re arguing in favor of gun control, you have no excuse not to realize somebody will bring up â€œBut donâ€™t guns save lives by helping people with self-defense?â€. And in fact, if youâ€™re arguing in favor of gun control, you had better have thought long and hardÂ yourselfÂ about whether or not guns save lives through self-defense. If youâ€™ve never considered that, you have no business having an opinion. But if youÂ haveÂ considered and rejected that, then you might as well run your audience through your thought process now (and sound more convincing) now rather than wait until some pro-gun person brings it up (and be caught flat-footed like Alice in the second example).
The logical conclusion of this process is that you address all the arguments, counterarguments, and countercounterarguments in the space youâ€™re covering, nobody can disagree with you, and youâ€™re self-evidently right. Sometimes this takes a lot of text, but better a long argument which is accurate and convincing than a short snappy argument which might be wrong or unpersuasive. Besides, by this point youâ€™ve absorbed all these other tips and hopefully write in an engaging way that makes your readers want to keep going no matter how many levels of countercountercountercounterargument you spring on them.
(Your other option here is just to put this stuff in footnotes and let your readers decide whether or not to go through them. Itâ€™s very satisfying to answer somebodyâ€™s stupid objection with â€œActually, I think youâ€™ll find I disproved that in footnote 17.â€)
Thereâ€™s a special variant of this you need when youâ€™re in shark-infested waters, debating very controversial things with very hostile people. Here the â€œcounterargumentâ€ is going to take the form of trying to destroy your reputation by using one of your comments, taken out of context, to prove youâ€™re a bad person with unconscionable beliefs who should never be listened to.
For example, suppose Iâ€™m trying to explain some social phenomenon and I mention that rich people get better grades in school than poor people. A hostile opponent could accuse me of making a stupid stereotype and saying that all rich people are better than all poor people; then he could condescendingly â€œcorrectâ€ me by saying that actually the within-class differences are larger than the between-class ones. Or might say that I need to realize school grades arenâ€™t the only thing and there are much more important determinants of peopleâ€™s worth as a human being. Or he might accuse me of being a Social Darwinist, and â€œcorrectâ€ me by saying that maybe this is because of the stresses of poverty.
Now, in fact I neither said nor meant any of those things. But if somebody accuses me of them, and I have to plead that I really didnâ€™t mean it that way, honest â€“ then they can double down and say that my protests of innocence are the surest sign of my guilt. Whether they succeed or not, Iâ€™m on the defensive. Weâ€™ve shifted from debating whatever point I wanted to make in the first place, to debating whether Scott is a monocle-wearing Social Darwinist who believes all poor people deserve to starve on the street.
The solution is really simple:Â anticipate and defuse counterarguments. If I wanted to make the class/grades point, it would go something like this:
 According to [study], students from families earning &gt;$100,000 score have an average high school GPA X points higher than students from families earning &lt; $20,000. This obviously doesnâ€™t mean all rich people do better than all poor people, and it doesnâ€™t rule out causes like the stress of poverty hurting peopleâ€™s brains. But it does suggest a possible explanation for [whatever phenomenon I was trying to use this to explain]. 
A related note: when talking about controversial things to a potentially hostile audience, look throughÂ every single sentenceÂ of your work and imagine how it would sound if it were quoted out of context and used as a summary of who you are as a human being. If you donâ€™t, eventually someone will try this and youâ€™ll be unprepared.</li>
  <li>Use strong concept handles
The idea of concept-handles is itself a concept-handle; it means a catchy phrase that sums up a complex topic.
Eliezer Yudkowsky isÂ really good at this. â€œbelief in beliefâ€œ, â€œsemantic stopsignsâ€œ, â€œapplause lightsâ€œ, â€œPascalâ€™s muggingâ€œ, â€œadaptation-executors vs. fitness-maximizersâ€œ, â€œreversed stupidity vs. intelligenceâ€œ, â€œjoy in the merely realâ€ â€“ all of these are interesting ideas, but more important theyâ€™re interesting ideas with short catchy names that everybody knows, so we can talk about them easily.
I have very consciously tried to emulate that when talking about ideas likeÂ trivial inconveniences,Â meta-contrarianism,Â toxoplasma, andÂ Moloch.
I would go even further and say that this is one of the most important things a blog like this can do. Iâ€™m not too likely to discover some entirely new social phenomenon that nobodyâ€™s ever thought about before. But there are a lot of things people have vague nebulous ideas about that they canâ€™t quite put into words. Changing those intoÂ crystal-clearÂ ideas they can manipulate and discuss with others is a big deal.
If you figure out something interesting and very briefly cram it into somebody elseâ€™s head, donâ€™t waste that! Give it a nice concept-handle so that theyâ€™ll remember it and be able to use it to solve other problems!</li>
  <li>Recognize that applying these rules will probably start disastrously
Thereâ€™s a pattern across almost all skills, where people start off doing things half-baked but sometimes with a bit of native talent. The experts teach them The Right Way To Do Things, and they switch to doing it in a stilted formulaic way that makes everybody else cringe. Eventually they become better and better. Finally, they do things that completely contradict the rules they were taught, and it works great. I think it was in the context of poetry that somebody said â€œLearn the rules first, then you can break them as much as you want.â€
Untrained natural writing is often bad, but at least honestly bad. Untrained writing that tries to force itself to do something because somebody told them it was a good idea isÂ much worse. Think of the old adage â€œIf youâ€™re giving a speech, start out with a joke.â€ Itâ€™s great advice when done right. Now imagine all the ways it could go wrong â€“ terrible jokes, inappropriate jokes, forced jokes, speeches that absolutely shouldnâ€™t start off with jokes, et cetera. A speech that doesnâ€™t start off with a joke is often good; a speech that shouldnâ€™t start out with a joke but has been forced into doing so never is. Eventually you end up shouting â€œJust use your instincts!â€ at people who do not actually have instincts.
Use the advice in this post wrong, and you end up transforming the famous quote from the Declaration of Independence into something like:
Although we agree King George has many good qualities, we nevertheless hold these truths to be more or less self-evident. Truth number one, that all men are created equal. For example, they should all be equally allowed to speak freely aboutÂ importantÂ issues like taxes. Itâ€™s possible that there might be some times they shouldnâ€™t be equal, like children having fewer rights than adults, but this are just minor exceptions. [insert picture of Liberty Bell here] Truth number two, that they are endowed by their Creator with certain inalienable rightsâ€¦
Almost the only good advice in any discipline is â€œdevelop instincts, then use themâ€. While youâ€™re waiting for the instincts to develop, or in order to push them along, itâ€™s sometimes helpful to hear some other peopleâ€™s advice. ButÂ do. not. force. it.
George Orwell ended his own list of writing advice with â€œBreak any of these rules rather than say something outright barbarousâ€. As usual, George Orwell is right.
I also like Piet Heinâ€™s commentary:
There is one art, no more, no less: to do all things with art- 
