<p>Figure out what youâ€™re going to say about the subject. You can do this by writing a rough draft (without the opening paragraph) or by making a list:</p>

<p>Children Should Be Consumed As Food</p>
<ul>
  <li>nutritious</li>
  <li>reduces the population</li>
  <li>teaches other children a lesson</li>
</ul>

<p>If youâ€™d rather just start writing than make lists, thatâ€™s fine. Write everything you can think of about the subject. Let it ramble. Donâ€™t worry about organization. Then, when youâ€™re done, compile a list from it. Put each sentence in a category.Â </p>

<p>Then, knowing what you have to say, go back and write your opening paragraph, explaining your subject and, in broad strokes, how youâ€™re going to approach it:</p>

<p>â€œYou may flinch at the idea of shoving your son or daughter into a preheated oven, but before you reject the idea, consider this: children are nutritious, and by eating them, youâ€™ll reduce the population. By eating naughty children, youâ€™ll send a message. Kids who havenâ€™t yet become pies, casseroles, and sandwiches will think twice before torturing the cat or tramping all over your lawn.â€</p>

<p>Itâ€™s fine if you later add something (â€œChildren are so annoying on airplanesâ€) or make a cut (â€œMaybe theyâ€™re not so nutritious.â€) Writing isâ€“or should beâ€“a fluid activity. Expect to make many drafts before youâ€™re done.Â </p>

<p>Try to be as sensual as possible. That is, try to cause sights, smells, tastes, sounds, movements, and textures to come into the readerâ€™s mind, so that he feels orÂ 
experiences
what youâ€™re writing about. I often have to make multiple drafts to achieve this. My first will be a sort of â€œjust the facts maâ€™amâ€ info-dump:</p>

<p>â€œThe perfect murder is hard to pull off. Policing has become extremely advanced, what with fiber analysis and DNA testing. There are security cameras everywhere, and weâ€™ve all given away too much information about ourselves online. The professional killer needs to plan ahead and watch his back.â€</p>

<p>Okay. What can I do to make that paragraph more effective? The more sensual I make it, the more the reader is likely to think about it and remember it.Â </p>

<p>Letâ€™s look at the first sentence. â€œâ€¦ hard to pull offâ€ is boring. Itâ€™s vague. It doesnâ€™t evoke an image. So I riff for a while. I usually press return multiple times between that sentence and the nextâ€“or use a blank sheet of paperâ€“and brainstorm:</p>

<p>â€
